## Task Management System

`my-tasks/` uses a hub-and-spoke model: `tasks.md` is the single source of truth and the four view files are read-only Dataview lenses that filter it. Never add tasks directly to a view file.

### tasks.md — the backlog

Tasks are grouped under headings that identify their source context:

```markdown
### YYYY-MM-DD — <meeting or context name>

- [ ] do the thing #this-week [[YYYY-MM-DD-1on1-alice.smith@acme.com]]
- [x] done thing #this-week [[YYYY-MM-DD-1on1-alice.smith@acme.com]]
```

Each task has three components:

| Component | Purpose | Values |
|-----------|---------|--------|
| `- [ ]` / `- [x]` | Completion state | open or done |
| `#horizon-tag` | Time horizon — controls which view shows the task | `#today`, `#this-week`, `#this-month`, `#this-quarter` |
| `[[wikilink]]` | Link to the source note that generated the task | any note in the vault |

### View files — Dataview lenses

Each view file contains a single Dataview query that reads `tasks.md` and filters by its tag. Example from `this-week.md`:

```
TASK
FROM "my-tasks/tasks.md"
WHERE !completed AND contains(text, "#this-week")
SORT file.mday DESC
```

View files update automatically as tasks are added or checked off in `tasks.md`. They are never edited manually.

### Workflow

1. After a meeting, add action items to `tasks.md` under a heading with the meeting date and name
2. Tag each task with the appropriate horizon (`#today`, `#this-week`, `#this-month`, `#this-quarter`)
3. Link each task back to the source note with `[[wikilink]]`
4. Open the relevant view file to see what is due in that horizon
5. Check tasks off in `tasks.md` — views update automatically

### Why the wikilink matters

The `[[wikilink]]` on each task is not decorative. It connects the task to the meeting or note that generated it. In Obsidian's graph, you can navigate from any task to the conversation behind it, and from any meeting note, see all the tasks it produced. This is one of the primary connection types the vault is built around.

