## Core Conventions

**Inbox as the entry point.** All externally generated content (meeting notes, synced docs) lands in `inbox/` first. A skill or manual process routes it to the right place. Nothing lives permanently in `inbox/`.

**Email as identity — and as uniqueness guarantee.** Use email addresses — not display names — as primary identifiers for people in every filename that relates to a person. This is not just for organization: Obsidian resolves `[[wikilinks]]` by filename across the whole vault, so a file named `action-items.md` inside a person's folder is indistinguishable from another `action-items.md` elsewhere — the graph breaks. Including the email in the filename makes every file globally unique, which is what makes the connection graph reliable. This applies to you (the user) as much as to anyone else.

**Lowercase kebab-case everywhere.** All filenames and folder names use lowercase words separated by hyphens — no spaces, no underscores, no capitals. Email addresses embedded in filenames are the only exception: use them exactly as they are, since they are identifiers, not descriptive text. This rule applies to every file in the vault, including your own.

**ISO 8601 dates in filenames.** Always prefix time-bound files with `YYYY-MM-DD`. This keeps folders sorted chronologically without any plugin or database.

**Flat files, deep folders.** Keep individual notes atomic. Use folder hierarchy to express context (project, person, time period) rather than cramming context into long filenames.

**Plain text over databases.** Everything is Markdown. The system works without Obsidian — any text editor, any OS, any decade.

